               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-415" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-415" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-415" type="surname" value="DALTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-415" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN DALTON.</persName>
                  </hi> I am a silk-draper, in South-place, Finsbury—Farrell was in my employ. I lost seven yards of silk—I accused✗ him of taking it, he said he did not take it—he was what is called a maker-up, and he cut off certain lengths of one or two yards, and gave them to Pulford—these are them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-416" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-416" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-416" type="surname" value="JENKINSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-416" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN JENKINSON</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman G</hi> 53.) I went to South-place and saw Pulford—after some time Farrell came, put his hand in his breast, and gave something to Pulford, who went towards Ropemaker-street—I went and stopped him, I searched his pocket and found nothing—I took off his hat and found these pieces of silk—I took him, and then took Farrell.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Pulford's Defence.</hi> Farrell is my brother-in-law; he gave it me, and told me to sell it; I did not know it was stolen.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
